जनक|janaka
 (I)--(king of मिथीला) one of the twelve sages who knew the nature of the धर्म ordained by Hari. Son of Nimi, born by churning his dead body and hence known Mithila. He was Vaideha, born of a विदेह। He founded the city of मिथिला. His son was उदावसु. Father of सीता. {{F}}1:  भा. VI. 3. २०; IX. १३. १३-14; X. ७१. 9; वा. ८९. 2; Vi. IV. 5. २२-4; १३. १०३.{{/F}} In his sacrifice याज्ञवल्क्य won a prize for learning while शाकल्य was humbled for pretended superiority. Father-in- law of राम. {{F}}2:  Br. II. ३४. ३३-68; III. ३७. २२; ६४. 2;{{/F}} In the अश्वमेध Yajn5a of his, साकल्य was [page१-623+ ३५] ruined on account of his conceit by taking part in a disputa- tion; Janaka wanted to know the best among the learned assembled and set apart ११,000 crores, much gold, villages and servants to be given as present to him; in the disputa- tion each took part but याज्ञवल्क्य ultimately threw out the challenge. साकल्य questioned this and put to him a number of questions which were all answered. याज्ञवल्क्य in his turn put him a single question, a wrong reply to it inviting instantaneous death; साकल्य agreed, and unable to answer his question, was gathered to his ancestors; {{F}}3:  वा. ६०. ३२-62; ८९. 5; Vi. III. १८. ८५-90.{{/F}} told by the sage Asita what the Earth narrated to him about the ignorance of kings who without subduing themselves, try to subdue others. {{F}}4:  Vi. IV. २४. १२७-136.{{/F}}

