पुरञ्जन|puranjana
 (I)--a King of extensive learning, had a friend whose name and behaviour were not known; went in search of a suitable place for the realisation of various pleasures; this he found in a city of nine entrances resembling [page२-345+ ३८] भोगवती on the southern side of the हिमालयस्. By accident he met a charming lady protected by a serpent and followed by a number of ladies and men; moved by her charms he requested her to be his wife and she agreed; For a hundred years they continued to enjoy pleasures; पुरञ्जन used to visit the kingdoms, विभ्राजित, Saurabha, दक्षिण and Uttara पाञ्चालस्, ग्रामक, वैशस and others through the different entrances of the city guarded by the Superintendent; influenced by her charms he came com- pletely under her control; mad with desire for hunting, once he left his queen and went to the forest and after killing many a game, he returned home and desired to meet the queen whom he found lying on the bare ground in misery; he consoled her and once more yielded to her love and influence at the cost of his youth; he had ११०० sons and ११० daughters for whom he found worthy wives and suitable bridegrooms; he was then engaged in animal sacri- fices, when the followers of चण्डवेग, a Gandharva, attack- ed the city of पुरञ्जन and the Superintendent defended it single-handed for १०० years. This placed the citizens and the kinsmen in misery. A daughter of काल, once in the company of पूरु went to Bhaya, the Lord of the Yavanas to marry him; he adopted her as his sister; with her and his brother प्रज्वार he set out to wander in the world; in his tour the Yavanas attack- ed the city of पुरञ्जन; प्रज्वार burnt it down; पुरञ्- jana was seized and taken to the Yavana camp; the sacrificial animals tore him to pieces; was born as the daughter of Vidarbha राजसिम्ह; married by Malayadhvaja पाण्ड्य and gave birth to a daughter and seven sons, all kings of the द्राविड country. When the पाण्ड्य left for penance she went with him and served him; she wailed at his death; and when about to give up her own life, a Brahmana who called himself her friend consoled her by saying that he and she were once the two Hamsas of मानस and that she took to a household life and underwent all miseries; instructed thus she recollected her old status and remained calm; {{F}}1:  भा. IV. chh. २५-28 (whole).{{/F}} an allegory [page२-346+ ३४] for जीव and परमात्मन्; पाञ्चालस् are the five senses while the nine entrances to the city refer to the nine द्वारस् of the body; sometimes the जीव is a male sometimes a female, and sometimes God, and sometimes man or beast in accordance with Karma. {{F}}2:  Ib. IV. २९. 2-9, २९.{{/F}}

